article.headline: New Mexico State 53, UTEP 50
article.story:
LAS CRUCES, N.M. (AP) -- Aggie Princess Moore scored 20 points
Sunday to lead New Mexico State over UTEP 53-50.

Moore led New Mexico State on 7-of-11 shooting from the field
and went a perfect 2-for-2 from behind the 3-point line.

Senior guard Sinnamonn Garrett -- selected by Sun Belt Conference
head coaches as the league's Preseason Player of the Year -- added
11 points, while Ana Marisa Perez added 8 in the second half.

Forward Angie McGee led UTEP with 17 points, while Marta Dydek
and Ana Valtierra scored 8 points each for the Miners.

The Aggies opened the game with two straight 3-point baskets,
but the Miners battled back to take the lead at 11-10 with 9:44
left in the first half after a 3-pointer by Stephanie Rayos.

The Miners closed out the first half with a 4-1 run, giving UTEP
a 26-20 lead.

New Mexico State came out firing in the second half, including
14 of Moore's 20 points. She hit a 3-pointer in the first minute of
the period to bring the Aggies back to within 3 points at 26-23.
Garrett then tied the game at 26.

The Aggies eventually took the lead but the Miners put together
an 8-2 run over three minutes to take a 5-point lead at 42-36 with
8:36 to go. A 3-pointer by Perez capped an answering 5-0 run by the
Aggies that cut UTEP's lead to one at 42-41 with 6:20 left in the
game.

A steal and a breakaway lay-up by Moore put the Aggies in the
lead at 45-44 with 3:54 to go, and the Aggies led for the rest of
the game.

The Aggies shot 36 percent from the floor and 40 percent from
the 3-point line. The Miners shot 40 percent for the game and 31
percent from the 3-point arc.

The Aggies (2-0) now hold a 42-20 advantage against the Miners
(0-1), with the Aggies winning the last four meetings.
